The '''Ndiva Women’s Film Festival''' ('''NWFF''') is an African film festival for women filmmakers and audiences, established in [[Accra]], [[Ghana]] in 2017.<ref>John Elliot Hagan[https://www.thefinderonline.com/art-entertainment/item/8528-ndiva-women-s-film-festival-launched Ndiva Women’s Film Festival launched], ''The Finder'', 27 June 2017.</ref> The founder and executive director of NWFF is Aseye Tamakloe.<ref name=myjoyonline>[https://www.myjoyonline.com/entertainment/2017/september-28th/commonwealth-endorses-ndiva-womens-film-festival.php Commonwealth endorses Ndiva Women's Film Festival], myjoyonline.com, 28 September 2017.</ref>
The first NWFF, targeted at African women filmmakers and women of African descent, ran from 1-3 November 2017.<ref name=myjoyonline/> The scope of the second NWFF, held 1-3 November 2018, was widened to include women filmmakers worldwide.<ref>[https://afaccra.org/evenements-culturels/evenements-a-venir/ndiva-womens-film-festival-film-screenings/ Ndiva Women's Film Festival - Film Screenings]</ref> The opening film was ''The Life of Esteban'' by [[Inés Eshun ]] and the closing film was ''Potato Potahto'' by [[Shirley Frimpong Manso]].<ref>[http://africanwomenincinema.blogspot.com/2018/10/ndiva-womens-film-festival-2018.html Ndiva Women’s Film Festival 2018 – Official Selection - Accra, Ghana - 1-3 November]</ref>
